CONTEXT: A telecom company wants to use their historical customer data to predict behaviour to retain customers. We have to analyse all relevant customer data and develop focused customer retention programs.

def pie_chart_and_count_plot(col_name):
    # initialising subplots
    figure, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)

    # setting figure parameters
    figure.set_figheight(7)
    figure.set_figwidth(15)
    
    #setting axes titles
    ax[0].set_title(f'Pie Chart of {col_name}')
    ax[1].set_title(f'Count plot of {col_name}')

    # plotting the distribution
    telecom_df_copy[col_name].value_counts().plot.pie(ax=ax[0],autopct='%1.1f%%')
    sns.countplot(x=col_name,data=telecom_df_copy,ax=ax[1],hue='Churn')

    plt.show()

In [27]:
def calculateLowerAndUpperFence(col_name):
    Q1 = np.percentile(a=telecom_df_copy[col_name],q=25) # 25th percentile
    Q3 = np.percentile(a=telecom_df_copy[col_name],q=75) # 75th percentile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1 # inter-quartile-range
    cut_off = 1.5 * IQR
    # limit for outliers
    lower_fence = Q1 - cut_off
    upper_fence = Q3 + cut_off
    return lower_fence,upper_fence
In [28]:
def number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence):
    outliers = np.where((telecom_df_copy[col_name] < lower_fence) | (telecom_df_copy[col_name] > upper_fence))
    number_of_outliers = len(outliers[0])
    return number_of_outliers
In [29]:
def plotHistogramAndBoxPlotWithOutliers(col_name):
    # initialising subplots
    figure, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)

    # setting figure parameters
    figure.set_figheight(5)
    figure.set_figwidth(15)

    #setting axes titles
    ax[0].set_title(f'Distribution plot of {col_name}')
    ax[1].set_title(f'Box plot of {col_name}')

    # plotting the distribution
    sns.histplot(data=telecom_df_copy[col_name],ax=ax[0],kde=True,color='g')
    sns.boxplot(x=telecom_df_copy[col_name],ax=ax[1])

    plt.show()

    # figuring upper and lower limits
    lower_fence,upper_fence = calculateLowerAndUpperFence(col_name)

    # logical selection of outliers
    no_of_outliers = number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence)
    print(f'The number of outliers for {col_name} are {no_of_outliers}')

Observations:¶

  • As seen from above analysis, there is huge imbalance between the classes in the target variable.
  • This should be fixed by bringing in balanced data for the target classes or there can be some techniques applied before building the model. If we do not treat the data before model building, the model will be more inclined to one of the target class than the other. Some techniques used are:
    • Use metrics like precision, recall, F1-score.
    • Over-sampling tries to balance dataset by increasing the size of rare samples, rather than getting rid of abundant samples using SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique).
    • Under-sampling balances the dataset by reducing the size of the abundant class.
  • We will use over-sampling and only on train data because:
    • we don't want to loose on data that would be helpful for classification.
    • we shouldn't be over-sampling all the data, because model performance is judged on test or unseen data.
  • But this won't have generally an effect in our case, because bagging or random forest will do random-sampling.

We can also carry out Hypothesis testing to see different statistics.¶

In [44]:
# one-way ANOVA

# IMPORTING NECESSARY LIBRARIES
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

alpha = 0.05 # confidence interval
In [45]:
for col in non_categorical_columns:
    #performing the test
    stat, p_value = f_oneway(telecom_df_copy[col],X_train_res[col],X_train[col],X_test[col])

    #comparing values with alpha to arrive at a conclusion
    if p_value <= alpha:
        print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value,6)} < {alpha} (alpha) we reject the Null hypothesis.')
        print(f'{col.upper()} are different.')
    else:
        print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value,6)} > {alpha} (alpha) we fail to reject the Null hypothesis.')
        print(f'{col.upper()} are same.')
    print('*'*25)

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred,labels=[0,1]) # getting the confusion matrix
    
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=[i for i in actual_labels], columns=[i for i in pred_labels]) # confusion matrix data frame
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm_df,annot=True,fmt='g') # plotting the heatmap
    plt.show()

Observations:¶
    

  • There was a drop in accuracy for train data but the test data accuracy improved. Thus, the model was generalised and not over-fit.
    • 

  • We can improve the accuracy by going for Ensemble Techniques, which combines various models and comes up with better predictions as compared to a single model.
    • 

  • Various Ensemble Techniques that can be used are:
      

    • Bagging(Bootstrap Aggregation): builds homogeneous models parallely with random sampling with replacement(bootstrapping), and combining the results(aggregation). The base model is a high-variance model.
      • 

    • Random Forest: builds an ensemble of decision trees with random sampling with replacement and random feature selection to make tree in the ensemble different.
      • 

    • AdaBoosting(Adaptive boosting): builds homogeneous models sequentially with each model in the sequence trying to reduce the higher weighted misclassifications from the previous models. The base model is a high-bias model.
      • 

    • Gradient Boosting: builds homogeneous models sequentially with each model in the sequence trying to reduce the gradient(residual) from the previous models. The base model is a high-bias model.
      • 

    

    • 



NOTE:


    

  • In Bagging base estimators are complex.
    • 

  • In Boosting base estimators are simple.
    •

Trying different ensemble methods for the best model¶
    

  • We can use K-Fold Cross Validation Technique
    • 












In [110]:



     


from sklearn import model_selection



     















In [111]:



     


# model initialisations
dTree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)  # Decision Tree Classifier

dTreeR = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1,max_depth=4)  # Regularized Decision Tree Classifier

bgcl = BaggingClassifier(random_state=1)  # Bagging Classifier

rfcl = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1) # Random Forest Classifier

abcl = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1) # AdaBoost Classifier

gbcl = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1) # Gradient Boost Classifier

# initialising models in key-value tuples
models = []
models.append(('DT', dTree))
models.append(('DT_R', dTreeR))
models.append(('RF', rfcl))
models.append(('BAGGING', bgcl))
models.append(('ADA_BOOST', abcl))
models.append(('GRAD_BOOST', gbcl))

# evaluate each model in turn
results = []
model_names = []
for model_name, model in models:
    kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=1,shuffle=True)
    cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model,X,y, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
    results.append(cv_results)
    model_names.append(model_name)
    msg = model_name + ': ' + str(cv_results.mean()) + ' (' + str(cv_results.std()) +')'
    print(msg)

# boxplot algorithm comparison
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
fig.suptitle('Algorithm Comparison')
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(model_names)
plt.show()

RF: 0.789530664037243 (0.017832761105140777)
BAGGING: 0.7740317470580629 (0.016934449988267604)
ADA_BOOST: 0.8020464244148455 (0.013298747034263874)

    • 

  • ROC-AUC curve also suggests the same.
    • 












Tuning hyperparameters of Gradient Boost Classifier¶










I tried changing various random values for parameters like learning_rate, n_estimators, min_samples_leaf, max_depth, max_features of a Gradient Boost Classifier but found out that the highest accuracy for unseen test data and a more generalised model which did well both on train and test data was GradientBoostClassifier(max_depth=3,n_estimators=100). Hence I chose this model for classification of this dataset.

Observations:¶
    

  • There is a very high imbalance in the datapoints of the target feature.
    • 

  • This doesn't have a major effect in tree based classifiers.
    • 

  • But in other kind of classifiers target imbalance should be strictly taken care of either by resampling techniques or gathering balanced data points.
    • 

  • For the above telecom data set I chose Gradient Boost Classifier because of high accuracy and high AUC.
    • 

  • The most important features are Contract, tenure, MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges.
    • 

  • Senior Citizens are less likely to churn.
    • 

  • Customers with partners, more dependants, no online security, no tech support, on month-to-month contract are more likely to churn.
    • 

  • Rate of churn is more in the first 12 months of the tenure.
    • 

  • So overall we can focus on providing better online security with better tech support for atleast 12 months of the tenure to lower the churn rate.
    • 

  • For above classification we can also use other boosting classification frameworks like LightGBM, XGBoost, CatBoost which are very fast, lightweight and dynamic.
    •
